Lab 1 - A Simple Spring Boot REST Application

In this lab we will build a simple "Hello World" API using Spring Framework and Spring Boot. We will use the Spring Initializr at https://start.spring.io/ to establish most of the boilerplate structure. The API will implement a single resource, "/hello" that returns a JSON object that contains a greeting. An optional step will define a “/customer” resource. We will write unit tests for everything we code.

Part 1 - Generate project skeleton from Spring Initializr

__1. Open https://start.spring.io/

__2. Choose the following options:

Project:

Gradle – Groovy

Language:

Java

Spring Boot:

Select the lowest stable version (3.2.6 at the time of this writing)

Group:

com.webage

Artifact:

10-spring-boot-simple

Name:

10-spring-boot-simple

Package name:

com.webage

Packaging:

Jar

Java:

Version 21. The choice depends on the JDK version you have installed, and the version of Gradle.

__3. Open “Add Dependencies”. Add the following dependencies:

  • Type “web” to find the “Spring Web” dependency. Click the selection to add it.

  • Type “devtool” to find the “Spring Boot Dev Tools” dependency. Click the selection to add it.

__4. Click the Generate button. This will download a 10-spring-boot-simple.zip to your downloads folder.

__5. Find the zip file and extract the contents.

__6. Within the extracted archive you will find a 10-spring-boot-simple folder. Move this folder to the location of your other lab files, for example C:\LabFiles\ .

Part 5 - Explore the project

The project generated by Spring Initializr is largely structure and configuration intended to provide a quick starting point for a Spring Boot project. It is not intended to be a code generator to be used to write your Java / Spring Boot code.

__1. Take a moment to explore the structure and artifacts that are setup:

  • Open build.gradle. Notice the following:

    • Spring Boot is included with a specific version. The source code of this plugin can be found in GitHub at https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/main/spring-boot-project/spring-boot-tools/spring-boot-gradle-plugin/build.gradle

    • The io.spring.dependency-management will be key to eliminating our need to explicitly specify version for most dependencies. The source code of this plugin can be found in GitHub at https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/main/spring-boot-project/spring-boot-dependencies/build.gradle .

    • The Java version can be set here in build.gradle.

    • The repositories section describes where dependencies can be downloaded from. For security purposes, many companies like to override this to use their own privately hosted repositories.

    • Only a few “starter” dependencies are listed. Each refers to another build.gradle file containing a curated set of dependencies. For example, the spring-boot-starter-web file is located at https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/main/spring-boot-project/spring-boot-starters/spring-boot-starter-web/build.gradle .

    • The dependencies are not configured with versions. This is intentional; all versions are set according to io.spring.dependency-management. Versions only need to be specified if there is a reason to override.

  • Open Application.java in src/main/java/com/webage. Notice:

    • The @SpringBootApplication annotation marks this class as the “main” class in the application. It also means this class can be used as a @Configuration class to define @Beans, and that by default Spring Boot will attempt to AutoConfigure beans for us.

    • A single public static void main(String[] args) method. In Java, such methods are invoked from the command line. This will serve as the main entry point to the application.

    • The SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args); code starts the Spring application context. It loads all of the bean definitions found in Application.class, which happens to be the same class the main method itself is running in. The code generated by Initializr would not have reason to define any beans for us, so the rest of the class is empty.

  • Open application.properties in src/main/resources. Here we can define any properties we wish to control Spring Boot’s behavior, or for our own purposes. You can substitute this file with application.yml if you prefer YAML format.

  • Open ApplicationTest.java in src/test/java/com/webage.

    • This is a JUnit test class. Tools like Gradle and Maven understand that classes under src/test/java are test classes to be used when we ask to test our code.

    • The @SpringBootTest instructs Spring Boot and JUnit to work together when this test is run. When the test starts it will automatically load the application context defined in the @SpringBootApplication class.

    • The @Test annotation is from JUnit. This marks this method as a test to run. Notice this method contains no code but is a test nonetheless; when run the application context will load, or will fail if there is a configuration issue.

__2. Open ApplicationTest.java and run the test:

  • In VS Code: Notice the green triangle in the editor’s “gutter”. Click on this to run either an individual test method or all tests in the class.

  • In Eclipse: Right-click on the class. Select Run As / Junit Test.

  • In IntelliJ: Right-click on the class. Select Run ‘ApplicationTests’

__3. Observe the test results.

Part 6 - Create a Simple REST Controller

At present, our application doesn’t do anything. Now we will add a controller which will respond to GET requests for the /hello resource.

__1. Create a new folder named “web” under src/main/java/com/webage.

__2. Create a new file called HelloController.java.

__3. Open the file. Place a @RestController annotation on the class, like this:

@RestController
public class HelloController {

This annotation identifies this class as a Spring MVC Controller.

__4. Create a method within this class: 

@GetMapping("/hello")
public String hello() {
	return "Hello World!";
}

This method responds to HTTP GET requests for the path “/hello”.

__5. Save your work.

__6. Run the Application using the earlier instructions. Open a browser to http://localhost:8080/hello. You should see “Hello World!” in your browser.

Part 7 - Create a Unit Test

Any code that we write in Java, we should test with JUnit. Take a moment to create a simple JUnit test.

__1. Create a new folder named “web” under src/test/java/com/webage.

__2. Create a new file within “src/test/java/com/webage/web” called HelloTests.java. Open the file.

__3. Create a new test method that looks like this:

    @Test
    public void testHello() {
        var controller = new HelloController();
        String result = controller.hello();

        assertNotNull(result);
        assertTrue(result.contains("ello"));
    }

The @Test annotation marks this method as a test method. The logic instantiates our HelloController and calls the hello() method. JUnit assertions verify that the result we received was not null and contained the substring “ello”.

__4. If needed, organize your imports by typing Alt – Shift – O.

__5. Run the test. It should pass.

Part 8 - (Optional) Create a More Complex REST Example

Now let’s make a slightly more complex case where we return a domain object as a JSON object.

__1. Create a new folder named “domain” under src/main/java/com/webage.

__2. Create a new file called Customer.java. Open the file.

__3. Alter the code to look like this:

package com.webage.domain;

public class Customer {
	long id;
	String name;
	String email;


	public long getId() {
		return id;
	}
	public void setId(long id) {
		this.id = id;
	}

	public String getName() {
		return name;
	}
	public void setName(String name) {
		this.name = name;
	}

	public String getEmail() {
		return email;
	}
	public void setEmail(String email) {
		this.email = email;
	}
	
}

__4. Save your work.

__5. Return to HelloController.java. Add this method:

    @GetMapping("/customer")
    public Customer getCustomer() {
        var customer = new Customer();
        customer.setId(1);
        customer.setName("Srinivas");
        customer.setEmail("mail@mail.com");

        return customer;
    }

This method responds to GET requests for the /customer resource. It creates a Customer with some hard-coded values. When it returns it, Spring MVC will convert the Customer into a JSON representation automatically.

__6. Save your work. Since DevTools is on the classpath, your application should automatically restart. If it does not, stop and restart the application using the earlier instructions.

__7. Open a browser to http://localhost:8080/customer . You should see a JSON representation in your browser.

  • Browsers do not format JSON by default. If you would like to see the JSON formatted you will need to install a browser plugin like “JSON Formatter” for Chrome.

Part 9 - Create a Unit Test for /customers (Optional

Any code that we write, we should test. Take a moment to create a simple JUnit test.

__1. Return to HelloTests.java. Create a new test method that looks like this:

    @Test
    public void testCustomer() {
        var controller = new HelloController();
        var result = controller.getCustomer();

        assertEquals (result.getId(), 1);
        assertEquals (result.getName(), "Srinivas");
        assertEquals (result.getEmail(), "mail@mail.com");
    }

The @Test annotation marks this method as a test method. The logic instantiates our HelloController and calls the customer() method. JUnit assertions verify that the result we received was not null and that its properties contain the expected values.

Note that this test was a true unit test, not an integration test. It did not test any of the interactions with Spring MVC, such as the translation to JSON. We will see integration tests that do this in the coming sections.

__2. If needed, organize your imports by typing Alt – Shift – O.

__3. Run the test. It should pass.

Lab 2 - Use Spring’s JdbcClient with Spring Boot

Spring provides many ways to interact with relational databases. One of the simplest is the JdbcClient.

Spring Boot removes much of the configuration needed to work with databases. For convenience, Spring Boot can set up an embedded database, which you can override with an external database later on. This is useful for testing and early development.

In this lab you will implement a Data Access Object by creating SQL queries and issuing them with a JdbcClient that is created by Spring Boot.

Part 1 - Import the Project

__1. In your IDE, open the C:\LabFiles\20-spring-boot-jdbc project.

  • For VS Code, go to File / Open Folder and select the folder.

  • For IntelliJ, go to File / Open and select the folder.

  • For Eclipse, go to File / Import. Select existing Gradle project, Next, and browse to the folder location.

Part 2 - Enable the Default Embedded Database

Spring Boot will auto-configure an embedded (in-memory) database for us if an implementation (H2, HSQL, or Derby) is on the classpath. It will also automatically populate the database with a schema and test data if we give it the correct setup.

__1. Open the build.gradle file in the 20-spring-boot-jdbc project.

__2. Look at the dependencies section and notice the dependencies marked in bold:

dependencies { 
	implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-web' 	implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-thymeleaf' 	implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-jdbc' 
	runtimeOnly 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-devtools' 
	runtimeOnly 'org.hsqldb:hsqldb' 
	testImplementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-test' 
}

__3. Verify that the application runs. Open the src/test/java/com/webage/ApplicationTests class. Run the tests. The test loads the application context and nothing else. The test should run successfully.

  • To run tests in VS Code, right-click in the code, select “Run Tests in Current File”.

__4. When the application runs, Spring Boot...

...notices that HSQLDB is on the classpath. It automatically creates a DataSource object for an embedded, memory-based instance.

...notices the schema.sql file in the root of the classpath. Since we are using an embedded database, it assumes you wish it to use this file to establish the database schema.

...notices the data.sql file in the root of the classpath. It assumes we wish it to run the SQL statements in this file to populate the database.

...creates a bean of type JdbcClient, because it thinks we might need one.

Part 3 - Complete the DAO Class

Let’s flesh out the implementation of the DAO class to actually perform the query. We'll use some convenience classes provided by the Spring Framework to make this relatively painless.

__1. Open src/main/java/com.webage.dao.PurchaseDAOImpl.

__2. Look for the getAllPurchases() method. It should look like this:

@Override
public List<Purchase> getAllPurchases() {
	String sql = "SELECT * FROM PURCHASE";
	// Replace this statement with the call to jdbcClient.
	return null
}

__3. Replace the line 'return null;' with a call to jdbcClient, so that the method appears as below:

	@Override
	public List<Purchase> getAllPurchases() {
		String sql = "SELECT * FROM PURCHASE";
		return jdbcClient
			.sql(sql)
			.query(new BeanPropertyRowMapper<Purchase>(Purchase.class))
			.list();

The JdbcClient executes the given SQL against the database and returns a List of Purchase objects. The tricky part is turning rows/columns returned in the result set into Purchase objects. Spring's BeanPropertyRowMapper class automatically maps database columns into the properties of the Purchase class, assuming that the column names match the property names. If you compare the 'schema.sql' file with the Purchase class, you will notice the alignment. If the columns did not match the properties, we would need to use a RowMapper and provide our own mapping logic.

__4. Save your work.

Part 4 - Integration Testing

Anything that we code, we should test. Spring makes it easy to write powerful integration tests to exercise our code. These tests can be run easily in the IDE or Continuous Integration tools like Jenkins.

__1. Open src/test/java/com/webage/dao/PurchaseDaoImplTests.java. Find the getAllPurchases() test method. Remove the @Disabled annotation from the method. Run the test, it should pass.

  • To run tests in VS Code, right-click within the code, select “Run Tests in Current File”.

Part 5 - Run the web application

__1. Verify that the application runs. Open the src/main/java/com/webage/App class. Run the class. The application should start, there should be no major errors in the console.

  • To run the class in VS Code, there is a “Run” option hovering over the public static void main() method.

  • If you receive an error about “Port 8080 was already in use”, be sure to stop any other application you have running from a previous exercise.

__2. Open a web browser to http://localhost:8080/browse. A web application should appear. You should see the results of our database query.

Part 6 - (Optional) Implement and Test additional DAO Methods

__1. Return to com.webage.dao.PurchaseDAOImpl. Find the getPurchase() method.

__2. Replace the 'return null;' line with a call to jdbcClient so that the method appears as below:

	@Override
	public Purchase getPurchase(int id) {
		String sql = "SELECT * FROM PURCHASE WHERE ID = ?";
		return jdbcClient
			.sql(sql)
			.param(id)
			.query(new BeanPropertyRowMapper<Purchase>(Purchase.class))
			.single();
	}

This implementation returns a single Purchase object, not a List. Note that the SQL statement contains a “?” - this is known as a “bind variable”. The “.param” method is used to set the parameter; if there were multiple parameters, simply call the .param methods in the matching order. The same BeanPropertyRowMapper technique is used to automatically maps database columns into the properties of the Purchase. The “.single” method is used instead of “.list” since we expect one and only one Purchase returned.

__3. Save your work.

__4. Open src/test/java/com/webage/dao/PurchaseDaoImplTests.java. Find the getPurchase() test method. Remove the @Disabled annotation from the method. Run the test, it should pass.

Part 7 - (Optional) Implement and Test Yet Another DAO Method

__1. Return to com.webage.dao.PurchaseDAOImpl. Find the savePurchase() method.

__2. Replace the '// Add code here.' line with a call to jdbcClient so that the method appears as below:

@Override
public void savePurchase(Purchase purchase) {
	String sql = 
	"insert into PURCHASE (CUSTOMERNAME, PRODUCT, PURCHASEDATE) values(?,?,?)";
	jdbcClient
		.sql(sql)
		.param(purchase.getCustomerName())
		.param(purchase.getProduct())
		.param(purchase.getPurchaseDate())
		.update();
}

This implementation assumes the incoming Purchase is correctly populated with valid data. We set the SQL statement, set each parameter in the order expected by the bind variables, and execute update; insert, update, and delete statements all use the jdbcClient’s update() method. No value is returned from an update.

__3. Save your work.

__4. Return to src/test/java/com/webage/dao/PurchaseDaoImplTests.java. Find the savePurchase() test method. Remove the @Disabled annotation from the method. Run the test, it should pass.

Lab 3 - Use the Spring Data JPA under Spring Boot

Java Persistence Architecture, or JPA simplifies data access by automatically generating SQL queries to manage the storage and retrieval of Java objects. Spring Data takes that idea one step farther to automatically generate data access or "Repository" classes for Java objects. All we need to do is make sure our Java objects are annotated correctly to contain the additional metadata required for database storage. Also, of course, we need to setup the software infrastructure.

In this lab you will annotate a set of domain objects and then use Spring Data to implement a storage repository for those objects.

Part 1 - Import the Project

__1. In your IDE, open the C:\LabFiles\30-spring-boot-jpa project.

  • For VS Code, go to File / Open Folder and select the folder.

  • For IntelliJ, go to File / Open and select the folder.

  • For Eclipse, go to File / Import. Select existing Gradle project, Next, and browse to the folder location.

Part 2 - Examine the Project

__1. Expand the 30-spring-boot-jpa project.

__2. Open build.gradle.There are a few items already setup in the project that you should take note of for your own projects:

  • 'build.gradle' contains two dependencies that are particularly important to this project:

dependencies { 
	implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-data-jpa' 
	runtimeOnly 'org.hsqldb:hsqldb' 
	testImplementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-test' 
}

  • These dependencies pull in the components required for Spring Boot to implement the Spring Data JPA framework, and also to use the embedded HSQLDB instance for testing.

  • This lab focuses on JPA components only. Therefore there are no web dependencies.

  • Notice that the version numbers are not specified. The are determined based on the version of Spring Boot we are using.

  • In src/main/resources, there are two files, data.sql and schema.sql, which establish the database schema and initial data load for the embedded database that we'll use for testing. Spring Boot will use these to populate the database at startup.

  • Also in src/main/resources, there is a file called application.properties. This file contains minimal configuration:

# Supress JPA DDL Generation:

spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=none



# Show JPA-generated SQL:

spring.jpa.show-sql=true

spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true

  • Hibernate has the ability to automatically generate the DB's schema on startup. Spring Boot assumes we would want this behavior since we are using an embedded database. While useful in some situations, we will instead opt to deliberately create our own schema and test data with the *.sql files above.

  • The project contains a pair of domain classes that we will use as a starting point for our repository.

__3. Verify that the application runs. Open the src/test/java/com/webage/ApplicationTests class. Run the tests class (in VS Code, right-click in the code, select “Run Tests in Current File”. The test loads the application context and nothing else. The test should run successfully.

Part 3 - Annotate the Customer Domain Class

We have a pair of domain classes, 'Customer' and 'Purchase' that are meant to model a set of purchases that might be made through an online store of some kind. There is a "Many-to-One" relationship between these classes; many purchases might be made by one customer. We haven't modeled the reverse relationship, although that might also be useful.

__1. Expand spring-boot-jpa > src/main/java > com.webage.domain.

__2. Open the Customer class.

__3. Add the '@Entity' and '@Table' annotations to the class as shown below. These annotations designate that the class should be managed by JPA and tell JPA what database table name to use for the class:

@Entity
@Table(name="CUSTOMERS")
public class Customer {

__4. Add annotations to the 'id' field so it appears as below. These annotations mark the 'id' field as the primary key of 'Customer' and tell JPA how it's going to be generated:

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.IDENTITY)
long id;

__5. The 'name' field in 'Customer' is modeled by a column called 'CUSTOMER_NAME' in the database table that we are using. So, the default mapping of field name to column name will not work in this case. Annotate the field as shown below to override the default name mapping:

@Column(name="CUSTOMER_NAME")
String name;

__6. Organize the imports by pressing Ctrl-Shift-O. Select jakarta.persistence.Entity, jakarta.persistence.Table and jakarta.persistence.Id.

__7. Save the file.

Part 4 - Annotate the Customer Domain Class

__1. Open the Purchase class inside 'com.webage.domain'.

__2. Add the '@Entity' and '@Table' annotations to the class as shown below. These annotations designate that the class should be managed by JPA and tell JPA what database table name to use for the class:

@Entity
@Table(name="PURCHASES")
public class Purchase {

__3. Add annotations to the 'id' field so it appears as below. These annotations mark the 'id' field as the primary key of 'Customer' and tell JPA how it's going to be generated.

@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private int id;

__4. Annotate the 'customer' field as shown below to tell JPA that it should load the value from an associated table.

@ManyToOne
private Customer customer;

__5. Organize the imports by pressing Ctrl-Shift-O. Select jakarta.persistence.* for the various JPA references.

__6. Save the file.

We now have a set of domain objects that should be recognized as JPA Entities that can be managed by JPA.



Part 5 - Create the Repository Interfaces

This is where we see the magic of the Spring Data JPA framework!

The project has two interfaces declared in the 'com.webage.repository' package. Spring Data uses these interfaces to automatically generate classes that implement the repository functionality. Let's have a look at one of them.

__1. Open the interface called CustomersRepository in the com.webage.repository package.

__2. Change this interface.

As you can see, there's really not much to these repository interfaces. They extend a standard interface called 'CrudRepository' that includes standard Create, Retrieve, Update and Delete methods. They use Java generic type definitions to indicate what data type the repository holds, and the data type of the primary identifier field.

That information is enough for Spring Data to fully implement this interface. We don't need to write any access code at all!

Part 6 - Integration Test

Spring Data JPA greatly reduces the amount of boilerplate code needed for most applications to work with databases, but it is still our responsibility to provide integration tests. Fortunately, Spring Boot makes this easy with test abstractions specific to working with databases.

__1. Open the PurchaseRepositoryTests class in src/test/java/com/webage folder.

__2. Remove the @Disabled annotation. Run this test. It should pass.

__3. Take a moment to explore the test logic:

    • @DataJpaTest – Loads the Spring application context when the JUnit test starts, but only applies configuration relevant to JPA tests. In our case, this means the DataSource (loaded with the schema and test data), our generated Repository classes, and a transaction manager. Web and service-layer components are not loaded. This makes the test run faster.

    • @Autowired – Acquires a reference to the Spring Data JPA generated repository.

    • @Test – Standard JUnit annotation for marking a method to run as a test.

    • @Transactional – Marks the test as a transactional test. Spring will rollback any database changes after the test finishes, regardless of success or failure.

    • Logic – Our test method obtains an existing Customer from the DB, creates a new Purchase, and calls our repository to persist it to the database. To be sure that the database was actually updated, we clear the EntityManager so it is unaware of the previous activity. The persist activity results in the purchase’s ID being populated from the database. We use this ID to retrieve the purchase and test that its values match what we provided.

@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<?> addCustomer(@RequestBody Customer newCustomer) {
    // Validate input:
    if ( newCustomer.getName()==null
        || newCustomer.getEmail() == null) { 
        return ResponseEntity.badRequest().build();
    }
    newCustomer=repo.save(newCustomer);

    // Location header will resemble 
    // "http://localhost:8080/customers/27"
    URI location =
        ServletUriComponentsBuilder
        .fromCurrentRequest()
        .path("/{id}")
        .buildAndExpand(newCustomer.getId())
        .toUri();

    return ResponseEntity.created(location).build();
}

Part 16 - Add a PUT Method Handler

The PUT method models an update to a particular customer. For instance to change the customer's email for customer id 4, we would PUT an updated object to '/customers/4'.

__1. Add the following method to the 'CustomerAPI' class:

@PutMapping("/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<?> putCustomer(
    @RequestBody Customer customer, 
    @PathVariable long id) {

    if (customer.getId()!=id
        || customer.getName()==null
        || customer.getEmail() == null) {
            return ResponseEntity.badRequest().build();
    }

    repo.save(customer);
    return ResponseEntity.ok().build();
}

__2. Organize the imports by pressing Ctrl-Shift-O.

__3. Save the file.

Notice that we're verifying the customer id in the supplied object matches the id that's in the path variable. If there's a difference, we return a 'badRequest' response.

@Override
public List<Customer> getAllCustomers() {
	RestClient restClient = RestClient.create(apiUrl());
	Customer[] customers = restClient
		.get()
		.retrieve()
		.body(Customer[].class);			
	return Arrays.asList(customers);
}

The method creates an instance of RestClient, sets the base URI, creates a GET request, then receives the returned Customers as an Array. A List is returned based on the contents of the array.

Lab 7 - Enable JWT-Based Security

This lab will implement a much more complex scenario than previous exercises. You will setup three separate applications, an authorization server, a resource server, and a client application. The authorization server will produce JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) at the bequest of the client application, which will use these to access resources on the resource server.




Running three separate applications on the same instance at the same time can be confusing. To help out, refer to this table to understand which application is running on which port:

Application

Port

Purpose

URI

Authorization Server

9000

Produce JWT’s for authenticated clients

http://localhost:9000/token

Resource Server

8000

Serves resources seen in other labs; Customers and Purchases

http://localhost:8000

Client

8080

Authenticates and obtains JWT from Authorization Server, passes JWT in requests to Resource Server

http://localhost:8080/browse



Part 1 - Import the Authorization Server

__1. In your IDE, open the C:\LabFiles\70a-spring-boot-security-auth-server project.

  • For VS Code, go to File / Open Folder and select the folder.

  • For IntelliJ, go to File / Open and select the folder.

  • For Eclipse, go to File / Import. Select existing Gradle project, Next, and browse to the folder location.

Part 2 - Examine the Project

The project defines our authorization server. The purpose of the authorization server is to provide authenticated clients with JWTs.

The authorization server defines a single POST /token endpoint protected by Spring Security HTTP Basic authentication. The authorization server will return a JWT containing claims identifying the subject’s identity and scope (permissions). The JWT will be signed with a private key which will prove that the key was produced by the authorization server and was not tampered with.

There are a few items already setup in the project that you should take note of for your own projects.

  • build.gradle:

    • The spring-boot-starter-oauth2-resource-server dependency which is unusual because 1) this lab does not use OAuth2 and 2) the application server is not the resource server. This dependency is included only because the JWT-specific classes for spring security are defined here.

    • Spring Security itself is a transitive dependency of the *-resource-server dependency. Explicit declaration would be redundant (but harmless).

    • devtools is included as usual to allow quick restarts when we change code.

    • spring-security-test is included onlybecause it is not defined within spring-boot-starter-test. It includes some extra features that we will use specific to security testing.

  • In src/main/resources/keys, there are two files representing a key pair. JWTs produced by this authorization server will be signed with the private key. Later the resource server will check the signature using the public key. This will prove to the resource server that the JWT is authentic and was not tampered with.

    • Note: key pairs can be produced several different ways, including use of the openSSL command line tool. To keep the lab simple, the key pair was generated for you.

  • Also in src/main/resources, application.properties defines the server’s port and key pair location.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/web/AuthController defines the /token endpoint.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/security/TokenService will contain all the logic needed to define and sign the JWT.

__1. Verify that the application runs. Open the src/main/java/com/webage/App class. Run the class. The application should start, there should be no major errors in the console.

  • In VS Code, there is a “Run” option hovering over the public static void main() method.

__2. Open a web browser to http://localhost:9000. The browser should produce a message that the authorization server is running.

Part 3 - Complete the SecurityConfig Class

__1. Open src/main/java/com/webage/security/SecurityConfig.

__2. At the bottom of the class, define an InMemoryUserDetailsManager @Bean to override Spring Boot’s default behavior. Have it define a user named "client" with a password "{noop}DoNotTell" ({noop} means the password will not be encypted – which is fine for the classroom.) Set the "read" authority on this user:

//  Override Spring Boot's default user with 

//  our own user, password, and authorities:

@Bean

public InMemoryUserDetailsManager users() {

    return new InMemoryUserDetailsManager(

        User.withUsername("client")

            .password("{noop}DoNotTell")

            .authorities("read")

            .build()

    );

}

      • TIP: To automatically organize imports, use Alt-Shift-O (in VS Code).

__3. Open src/main/java/com/webage/web/AuthController. Within the body of the class, define a variable of type TokenService named “tokenService”. Annotate this variable with @Autowired to have Spring dependency inject this reference:

@Autowired

TokenService tokenService;

__4. Below this definition, add code to respond to POST requests on the /token endpoint. The method should take one parameter of type Authentication and return a String. The method should return the result of a call the tokenService’s generateToken() method:

@PostMapping("/token")

public String token(Authentication authentication) {

    return tokenService.generateToken(authentication);

}


__5. Open src/main/java/com/webage/security/TokenService and review how the JWT is generated:

      • The generateToken() method converts the “authorities” from the Spring Security into a space delimited “scope” String. For example, if the user possesses ADMIN and READ-WRITE authorities, the scope in the JWT would be “ADMIN READ-WRITE”.

      • The JWT is built from a set of key value pairs called “claims”. The JWT’s subject is the authenticated user, the expiration time is one hour from present, and the scope – or permissions – are the authorities from Spring Security.

      • The “encoder” from Spring Security 1) base64 encodes the token and 2) signs it with the key pair.

      • The JWT returned to the caller is a simple String.

__6. Save all work. Restart the application if necessary.

Part 4 - Test the POST /token Method

Anything that we code, we should test. Spring provides a powerful mock testing framework that makes it possible to test our web endpoints, including security requirements, without actually running as a server and opening a port. This is useful as we do not need to worry about port conflicts with other processes running simultaneously.

__1. Open the src/test/java/com/webage/web/AuthControllerTests class.

__2. Comment out the @Disabled annotation on the two test methods. Run the tests, they should pass.

__3. Take a moment to explore the test.

      • These tests use the Mock MVC test framework included with Spring. It is a different form of testing web applications than we have seen so far.

      • The first test proves that our /token endpoint requires the caller to provide HTTP Basic authentication. We expect a 401 UNAUTHORIZED error if this is not the case.

      • The second test is more involved. It performs a POST request against the /token endpoint, providing HTTP Basic authentication using a valid user and password. We expect this call to result in a 200 OK.

      • But what about the JWT itself? To check this we use a decoder to base-64 decode the String and check the signature with the public key. We assert that the user’s name and scope match our input data.

Part 7 - Examine the Project

The project defines our resource server. It is largely the same as earlier JPA / REST labs except 1) there is no user interface and 2) all endpoint will require a JWT passed in the request.

  • build.gradle:

    • The spring-boot-starter-oauth2-resource-server dependency allows us to capture and decode incoming JWTs.

    • Spring Security itself is a transitive dependency of the *-resource-server dependency. Explicit declaration would be redundant (but harmless).

    • We no longer have the thymeleaf dependency since this application does not serve up web pages.

    • Devtools is included as usual to allow quick restarts when we change code.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/api/PurchaseAPI is similar to previous labs, returning REST responses for /purchases and /purchases/{id}.

  • The domain, repository, and service packages and schema.sql and data.sql files are also the same as previous labs.

  • In src/main/resources/keys, there is a single public.pem file. This is a copy of the public key from the authorization server project. The public key alone is necessary for the resource server to check the signatures of JWTs produced by the authorization server.

    • CRITICAL POINT: The resource server does not have, and does not need, a copy of the authorization server’s private.pem. Security of public-key cryptography depends on keeping the private key secret; the public key can be openly distributed without compromising security.

  • Also in src/main/resources, application.properties defines the server’s port and public key location.

  • In src/test/resources/keys, there are two test*.pem files. These are not the same public / private keys used by the application server. They are only used by our test logic, used to verify that signed JWTs can be successfully processed by our Spring Security configuration.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/security/SecurityConfig defines the security setup. We will adjust this Spring Security configuration in the next step.

Part 8 - Complete the SecurityConfig Class

__1. Open src/main/java/com/webage/security/SecurityConfig.

__2. Find the comment for PART 8a. Copy the following method into the class. It defines a method that will create a JwtDecoder object. The NimbusJwtDecoder from Spring Security can provide an implementation for us if we call its withPublicKey() method to set the public key:

//  Create a JwtDecoder to be used by Spring Security to decode incoming
//  JWTs and check their signatures.  Inject it with the public key from 
//  the authorization server:
private JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
    return NimbusJwtDecoder.withPublicKey(publicKey).build();
}


__3. Find the comment for PART 8b. Insert the following code into the securityFilterChain method. It instructs Spring Security to treat this application as a resource server receiving JWTs for authentication and authorization:

        // Define this application as an OAuth2 Resource Server:
        .oauth2ResourceServer((resourceServer) ->
           resourceServer.jwt( (customizer) -> 
                customizer.decoder(jwtDecoder()) 
            )
        )

  • Important: be sure to insert this code before the “.build()” method call.

__4. Save your work. Open src/main/java/com/webage/App class and run the application. Verify that there are no major errors in the console.

Part 9 - Test the Resource Server

__1. Open src/test/java/com/webage/api/PurchaseAPITests.

__2. Take a moment to review the test logic:

  • Spring Boot will launch this application on a random port and @Autowire is used to provide a TestRestTemplate, as we have seen before.

  • The @TestPropertySource will override any properties defined in application.properties with different values we wish to use for testing. In this case, we wish to test with a key pair that is unrelated to any other application.

  • The first test method verifies that any request submitted without a JWT will result in a 401 UNAUTHORIZED.

  • The second test method calls logic to create a JWT. It verifies that when such a token is sent in the Authorization header as a Bearer token, our Spring Security setup correctly decodes it and checks its signature. We expect a 200 OK in these cases.

  • The private methods are used to create and sign JWTs. We need to use legitimately signed JWTs in our test to ensure that Spring Security is processing them correctly. The logic seen here is very close to what is seen in the authorization server, but the key used are unrelated.

Part 12 - Examine the Project

The project defines our client. It is essentially a web application which makes calls to the authorization server to get JWTs, then the resource server to obtain resources.

  • build.gradle:

    • The *-web, *-thymeleaf dependencies are present to serve web content.

    • Only authenticated users will be allowed to use this web application, so Spring Security will be used to implement simple form-based authentication.

    • Testing will be a bit tricky; we will need to mock out both the authorization server and resource server in our tests. WireMock is a good library for doing this, though it isn’t included in the spring-boot-test dependency.

    • Devtools is included as usual to allow quick restarts when we change code.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/web/PurchaseController is similar to previous labs, returning REST responses for /browse and the root resource /.

  • src/main/java/com/webage/service/PurchaseServiceImpl is responsible for obtaining the purchases. To do this it references the AuthorizationServerDaoImpl and ResourceServerDaoImpl to do the remote calls.

  • The dao package contains the implementation classes for calling the authorization server and resource server. We will do most of our work here.

  • In src/main/resources, we have an application.yml to define the URIs and ports for the two remote servers. In Spring Boot, application.properties and application.yml are interchangeable; use whichever you find easier. We also override Spring Boot’s default username and password. (For our simple classroom application, we won’t define a full-fledged user store.)

  • Note that the client does not touch any databases, needs no SQL files, and needs no key pair information.

  • Notice that there is no SecurityConfig class! Our client relies on Spring Boot’s out-of-the-box configuration, which provides a basic login page and secures all endpoints. For a more complex configuration we would probably override the basic setup, but for our simple client this is sufficient.

Part 14 - Examine the AuthorizationServerDaoImpl class

__1. Open src/main/java/com/webage/dao/AuthorizationServerDaoImpl. This class is a client for calling the Authorization Server. We will use this as a model for completing our ResourceServerDaoImpl in the next section.

__2. Notice the following:

  • The @Value annotation is used to retrieve the authorization.server.* values from the environment.

  • The @Autowired annotation is used to obtain a reference to the RestClient bean. This is used to call the back-end server.

  • The serverUri() method is used to compose the full URI from the URI and port values. This is done to make these values easy to override during testing.

  • The getJwt() is the method that calls the authorization server to obtain a JWT.

    • It uses the RestClient to make an HTTP GET call to the URI

    • It uses HTTP Basic authentication to authenticate with the authorization server. This requires that each request contains an Authorization header with an encoded username and password. The headers.setBasicAuth() method will build this value for us.

    • We expect to receive a response body containing the JWT, so we define the return value as a ResponseEntity set to receive String objects.

__3. Keep this file open and use it in the next step.

Part 15 - Implement the ResourceServerDaoImpl class

__1. Open src/main/java/com/webage/dao/ResourceServerDaoImpl. This class is a client for calling the Resource Server. Complete its implementation based using the AuthorizationServerDaoImpl as a model. Try to complete the code on your own before looking at the solutions below.

__2. First, define two member variables of type String for the URI and port of the resource server. The @Value annotation can be used to populate these parameters. Look at application.yml for the names of the parameters.

__3. Next, add the @Autowired annotation to the declaration of the RestClient variable.

__4. Replace the code within the serverUri() function. Use the String.format() method to combine the URI and port values into a single String.

__5. Within the findAllPurchases() method, after the uri() method call, use the .header() method to define an Authorization header with a bearer token. The name of the header will be “Authorization”. The value will be the word “Bearer”, a single space, and the JWT value. Note that the JWT was passed into the findAllPurchases() method via parameter.

__6. After the .header() method, use the .accept() method to tell the resource server that we wish to receive a JSON response. The method takes a MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON parameter.

__7. Check the implementation of the findAllPurchasesById() method to see if your implementation of the .header() and .accept() methods was correct.

__8. Solution code is:

    @Value("${resource.server.uri}")  String uri;
    @Value("${resource.server.port}") String port;

    @Autowired
    RestClient client;

    private String serverUri() {
        return String.format(uri,port);
    }

    @Override
    public Iterable<Purchase> findAllPurchases(String jwt) {
       ResponseEntity<Purchase[]> responseEntity = client
          .get()
          .uri(serverUri() + "/purchases")
          .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + jwt)
          .accept(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
          .retrieve()
          .toEntity(Purchase[].class);
       return Arrays.asList(responseEntity.getBody());
    }

__9. Save your work

Part 16 - Test AuthorizationServerDaoImpl

Anything that we code, we should test. In order to test our AuthorizationServerDaoImpl, we will need to mock out the actual server. WireMock can be used to do this.

__1. Open the src/test/java/com/webage/dao/AuthorizationServerDaoImplTests class.

__2. Comment out the @Disabled annotation on the getJwt() method.

__3. Run the test. It should pass.

__4. Take a moment to explore the test. This one is quite complex:

  • The @SpringBootTest runs this test as a non-web environment. We are focusing on our call to the authorization server and nothing else.

  • The @TestPropertySource overrides the port for the authorization server with a random high-order port. This avoids conflicts with other applications that may be running.

  • The @BeforeEach JUnit method runs once before each @Test method. It is used to turn on the WireMock server and configure it with the port defined earlier.

  • The stubFor() method “programs” the mock. The mock will expect a POST call on the /token endpoint with an Authorization header setup for HTTP Basic. When this happens, the mock will return a sample token in a 200 OK response.

  • The @Test method itself is anticlimactic; we expect that calls to the getJwt() method will return a JWT. Note that the client is not concerned with the value of the JWT, but the resource server is.

__4. DEBUGGING: If you are receiving an error page, there are some things you can do to diagnose the issue:

      • Make sure the authorization server is running. An error such as “I/O error on POST request for "http://localhost:9000/token": null ” indicates the server is not running.

      • Make sure the resource server is running. An error such as “I/O error on GET request for "http://localhost:8000/purchases": null ” indicates the server is not running.

      • Make sure the client is using the same username and password as the authorization server. An error such as “Unauthorized: 401 ” would indicate they are out of sync. (Use “client” / “DoNotTell”)

Part 20 - Review

In this lab, we implemented JWT-based authentication and authorization. We build an authorization server which issued signed JWTs to the client application, we built a resource server which accepted and validated JWTs as authentication, and we build a client application which consumed both services. We also saw that all of our code can and should be tested using various automated tests.
